A debounce function ensures that a given function is executed only after a specified delay has passed since the last time it was invoked, which is useful for optimizing performance in scenarios like event handlers or API calls.

```javascript
function debounce(func, delay) {
  let timeoutId;
  return function(...args) {
    clearTimeout(timeoutId);
    timeoutId = setTimeout(() => func.apply(this, args), delay);
  };
}

// Example usage
const logMessage = debounce(() => console.log('Message logged after debounce!'), 300);

// Simulate rapid calls (e.g., on scroll or resize events)
logMessage(); // Won't log immediately
logMessage(); // Debounced; logs after 300ms from last call
logMessage(); // Still debounced
```

In this example, `logMessage` will only execute once, 300ms after the final invocation, preventing multiple rapid-fire logs.
